        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>April 23&#44; 54</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Rabbi Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I forward the<lb/> <sic>inclosed</sic> which I have<lb/> just <sic>recieved</sic> in a letter<lb/> from my brother.<lb/> The prospects in <placeName>Pal&#45;<lb/>estine</placeName>&#8212;politically &#38; socially<lb/> are entirely favourable<lb/> to agricultural <sic>persuits</sic>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Oh can you not<lb/> influence those who<lb/> have the control of the<lb/> funds which are in<lb/>tended for <placeName>Palestine</placeName> to<lb/> direct that a portion<lb/> of them be expended<lb/> in employing the</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>poor in learning agriculture&#44;<lb/> as you propose in the <date>Feb.</date><lb/> no of the &#8220;Occident.&#8221;</p>
			<p>There can be no objection.<lb/> Your English brethren<lb/> approve&#8212;certainly our<lb/> practical &#38; economical<lb/> Americans will also.<lb/> They must disearn<add>&#63;</add> the<lb/> great advantage of<lb/> aiding their brethren<lb/> to earn their own sub&#45;<lb/>sistence in preference<lb/> to supporting them for<lb/>ever in idleness.</p>
			<p>This place of appropri<lb/>ating your charities in<lb/> the <placeName>Holy Land</placeName>&#44; will cer<lb/>tainly become popular<lb/> in the minds of all<lb/> your reflecting brethren.</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>but as with any other<lb/> reform measure or new arrang<lb/>ment it will doubtless be<lb/> necessary to constantly<lb/> recommend and insist upon<lb/> its adoption.</p>
			<p>Dear Sir&#8212;allow me to<lb/> express the hope that in<lb/> view of the certainty of an<lb/> ultimate success&#44; &#38; of the<lb/> superior good to be attained&#44;<lb/> you will persevere with<lb/> all possible energy &#38; dili<lb/>gence until the effort you<lb/> have so properly commenced<lb/> is fully <sic>consumated</sic>.<lb/> Until those of your brethren<lb/> who leave the power&#44;<lb/> decide fully to have their<lb/> funds expanded in learning<lb/> the destitute in <placeName>Palestine</placeName></p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p>how to maintain <hi rend="underline">themselves</hi><lb/> and thus become permanently<lb/> relieved from their poverty&#8212;<lb/> Our colony would not desire<lb/> to assume any responsibility<lb/> in relation to the direction<lb/> or control in the least<lb/> degree of your funds&#44; which<lb/> should be continued at the dis<lb/>posal of the R<add>&#63;</add>.</p>
			<p>Our Farmers &#38; Mechanics<lb/> will afford the requisite in<lb/>struction &#38; gratis&#44; until<lb/> the men are sufficiently<lb/> advanced to support them<lb/>selves. Your Rabbis will<lb/> however disburse to them<lb/> their usual allowance in the<lb/> form of wages&#44; to enable them<lb/> as at present to support<lb/> their families while they</p>
          
